Good morning everyone. Today I'll present my project on AI computer vision for abnormal detection in pet care monitoring.

I'll cover four main topics: the background and motivation for this project, our methodology and how we built the system, the results we achieved, and finally our conclusion with future improvements.

Let me start with the background. Pet owners increasingly treat their pets as family members, which is driving significant growth in pet care services. AI shows great potential for pet behavior monitoring and safety. 

However, traditional pet sitting services lack real-time monitoring capabilities. This project addresses that gap by using AI computer vision to provide an automated, reliable monitoring system that ensures pet safety and maintains client trust.

Now let's move to the methodology. For location tracking, we use BLE Beacons equipped with an NRF52810 chip.

For the wearable device component, we use an ESP32S3 microcontroller with an OV5640 camera module. The device includes cooling fins and cooling fans to manage heat, and it's mounted on a chest harness with a power bank to enable extended operation.

For AI training, we selected the YOLO version 8s model. We trained it on 4220 images collected from Roboflow. Our data augmentation strategy includes geometric and color space transformations. We used an NVIDIA RTX4090 GPU for the training process.

The workflow operates as follows. First, two BLE beacons transmit location signals. The wearable device continuously receives these signals and calculates the distance between itself and each beacon. At the same time, the camera captures images at 10 frames per second. Both the calculated distance data and the images are sent to our backend system. The backend server contains various APIs and our AI model. When images arrive, the AI model analyzes them to detect pets, and if a pet is detected, it outlines the target and provides a confidence percentage. This information is displayed in the PetGuard iOS app. Simultaneously, the backend server receives the distance data and applies proximity logic. If the distance exceeds 1 meter or if a target pet is detected, the app triggers both an alert notification and automatic video recording.

Moving to the results, our AI detection model achieves a 92.5% confidence rate. It can detect humans, cats, and even combinations of humans and cats. Whenever a target is detected, the system automatically triggers the recording feature.

For the proximity and recording features, we can place BLE beacons near restricted areas, such as bedroom doors, to mark boundaries. When the wearable device comes within 1 meter of these beacons, the iOS app displays a proximity alert and recording automatically starts. Users can then review and playback recorded videos directly within the app.

In conclusion, our AI model achieves a high 92.5% detection confidence rate. The wearable device operates stably for over 2 hours on a single charge. The backend system maintains a latency under 200 milliseconds. The iOS app successfully includes live streaming, recording, and alert functionality. For future improvements, we plan to expand our dataset to over 10k images, add an LED module to handle low-light environments, implement Kalman filtering to reduce false alerts, add temperature sensors for intelligent fan control to save power, and finally move to cloud deployment for remote access capabilities.

